Article 38 After divorce, the parent that does not directly bring up the children has the right
to visit the children, and the other party has the obligation to give assistance.
ç¬¬ä¸‰åå…«æ¡ ã€ç¦»å©šåçš„å­å¥³æ¢æœ›ã€‘ç¦»å©šåï¼Œä¸ç›´æ¥æŠšå…»å­å¥³çš„çˆ¶æˆ–æ¯ï¼Œæœ‰æ¢æœ›å­å¥³çš„æƒåˆ©ï¼Œ
å¦ä¸€æ–¹æœ‰ååŠ©çš„ä¹‰åŠ¡ã€‚
The way and time for exercising the right of visiting children shall be agreed upon by the
parties concerned. In case no agreement is achieved, they shall be decided by the peopleâ€™s
court.
è¡Œä½¿æ¢æœ›æƒåˆ©çš„æ–¹å¼ã€æ—¶é—´ç”±å½“äº‹äººåè®®ï¼›åè®®ä¸æˆæ—¶ï¼Œç”±äººæ°‘æ³•é™¢åˆ¤å†³ã€‚
If the visit of either the father or mother is harmful to the soundness of the body and mind of
the children, the said right shall be terminated by the peopleâ€™s court. When the reasons for
terminating the said right disappear, the right shall be resumed.
çˆ¶æˆ–æ¯æ¢æœ›å­å¥³ï¼Œä¸åˆ©äºå­å¥³èº«å¿ƒå¥åº·çš„ï¼Œç”±äººæ°‘æ³•é™¢ä¾æ³•ä¸­æ­¢æ¢æœ›çš„æƒåˆ©ï¼›ä¸­æ­¢çš„äº‹ç”±æ¶ˆ
